                <ab>
                    <lb n="0"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>α<unclear>χ</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#_εκλῆς"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><seg part="F">εκλῆ<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></seg></name></persName><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>                    
                    <lb n="2a"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>            
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Intraduisible.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The only clear thing here is that line 2 has a personal name such as <foreign xml:lang="grc">Μενεκλῆς</foreign> or
                    <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φερεκλῆς</foreign>, both attested in Cyrenaica, either at the nominative or perhaps at the accusative case. The letters at line 1 might also 
                belong to a personal name.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
